Measures of Central Tendency

Measures of central tendency se hum data ka center samajhte hain,
- matlab wo value jo data ka typical ya representative value hoti hai.
- Yeh measures batate hain ke data kahan clustered hai.

  • Core Measures of Central Tendency:

    • Mean (Arithmetic Average)
    • Median
    • Mode
  • 1 Mean
    • Mean ko hum average bhi kehte hain.
    • Yeh wo value hoti hai jo data set ke central point ko represent karti hai.
    • Iska calculation simple haisabhi numbers ko add karo aur unka total number of items se divide karo.

  • 2 Median

    • Median wo value hoti hai jo data ko half mein divide karti hai.

    • Agar data sorted hai toh:

      • Odd number of data points: Median = Middle element
      • Even number of data points: Median = Average of two middle elements

Purpose Sab values ka average nikalna Mid wali value dikhana
Calculation Sum of all values number of values Sorted list ka center value
Use kab hota hai? Jab data symmetrical aur clean ho Jab data skewed ya uneven ho
Sorted Data chahiye? Nahi zarurat Haan zaroori hai
Kya represent karta hai? Central trend with balance True middle of data

Feature Mean Median Mode
Kya batata hai? Average value Middle value Most frequent value
Outlier sensitive? Yes No No
Categorical pe kaam? Nahi Limited Perfect
Numerical data? Yes Yes Yes
Condition / Situation Use Mean Use Median Use Mode Explanation
Balanced numerical data Yes Yes Rarely Mean aur Median dono accurate center dikhate hain
Data mein outliers hon No Yes Maybe Median zyada reliable hoti hai
Skewed (uneven) data No Yes No Median real center show karta hai
Normal (bell-shaped) distribution Yes Yes Maybe Sab close hotay hain koi bhi kaam kar sakta hai
Categorical data (e.g. Shirt, Pant) No No Yes Mode hi kaam karta hai most frequent value
Ordinal data (e.g. Poor, Good, Excellent) No Yes Yes Median + Mode dono useful average rank ya most frequent
Missing value fill numerical balanced Yes Yes No Mean ya Median use hoti hain
Missing value fill skewed/outlier data No Yes No Median safe hoti hai from distortion
Missing value fill categorical No No Yes Mode sabse zyada common value fill karta hai
Data center chahiye (center of tendency) Yes Yes No Center ke liye mean/median better hotay hain
Data summary (quick idea) Yes Yes Yes Teeno ka use ek sath bhi hota hai
ML: Standardization (x - mean / std) Required No No Mean required hota hai Standard Scaler ke liye
ML: Robust Scaler / Skewed Data No Yes No Median based scaling zyada stable hoti hai
User behavior ya product trend analysis No No Yes Mode se most common item find hota hai

Some More Measures of Central Tendency

  • 3 Geometric Mean
    • Geometric Mean aik multiplicative average hota hai.
    • Jab values multiply hoti hain (jaise: growth rate, population, investment), tab use hota hai..

Feature Simple (Arithmetic) Mean Geometric Mean
Formula (x + x + x + ... + x) / n (x x x ... x)^(1/n)
Data kis type ka hota hai? Jab values add ho rahi ho (e.g. marks) Jab values multiply ho rahi ho (e.g. growth rate)
Calculation logic Sab values ko add karo aur divide karo Sab values ko multiply karo aur root lo
Outlier ka effect Bohat zyada hota hai Kam hota hai
Zero allow karta hai? Haan Nahi (0 multiply hone se result 0 ban jata hai)
Negative values? Haan Nahi (odd roots of negative = complex number)
Use kab hota hai? Jab values ki simple average chahiye Jab values ratios ya % growth represent kar rahi ho
Real-world example Marks, height, age, exam score, salary Investment growth, interest rate, population growth
Result interpretation Central value of data Realistic average of %age or ratios
Graph mein look Center of gravity Slightly pulled toward smaller values
Use karo jab... Addition-based situations (score, marks) Multiplication-based (growth, interest, CPI)
Situation Use This Mean Reason
Student ke marks ka average Arithmetic Mean Marks add hote hain
Paisa 3 saal tak grow ho +10%, +30% Geometric Mean Compound growth multiply hota hai
Height ka average Arithmetic Mean Normal addition-based metric
Price Index (CPI, inflation) Geometric Mean Prices multiply hoti hain (inflation effect)
Machine learning ke ratios / growth Geometric Mean Ratios aur scale zyada accurate hota hai
Mixed + Negative values present Arithmetic Mean Geometric mean invalid hoti hai negative/0 pe
  • 4 Harmonic Mean
    • Harmonic Mean tab use hoti hn jab values ratio form mein hoon (e.g. speed, km/hr, Rs/unit).
    • Ye lowest average hota hai aur most accurate jab distance/time involve ho.

Mean Type Core Difference Simple Equation Kab Use Karein? (Use-case)
Arithmetic Mean Sab values ka additive average (x1 + x2 + x3 + ... + xn) n Jab values add ho rahi ho (marks, salary, height)
Geometric Mean Values ka multiplicative average nth root of (x1 x2 x3 ... xn) Jab values percent ya ratio form mein ho (growth, ROI)
Harmonic Mean Values ka inverse average (per-unit based) n (1/x1 + 1/x2 + ... + 1/xn) Jab values speed ya rate ho (distance/speed, Rs/unit)
Type Use When...
Arithmetic Mean Jab normal average chahiye (additive context)
Geometric Mean Jab growth, percentage ya compound effect ho
Harmonic Mean Jab rate, speed, ya unit-per-time cheezen ho

  • 5 Trimmed Mean

    • Trimmed Mean main kuch lowest aur highest values remove ki jati hn
    • Baki values ka normal average (mean) nikal detay ho.
    • Ye outliers (extreme values) ka effect kam kar deta hai, aur zyada reliable average deta hai.

     Step 1: Data ko sort karo
 Step 2: n = total number of items
 Step 3: x = trimming percentage (0.1 for 10%)
 Step 4: Remove x*n lowest values aur x*n highest values
 Step 5: Bachi hui values ka average lo
In[1]:
# apply in function
def tm(data, percent):
    data = sorted(data)
    n = len(data)
    t = int(n * percent)
    return sum(data[t : n - t]) / (n - (2 * t))
In[2]:
data = [10, 12, 13, 15, 17, 300]
data
Out[2]:
[10, 12, 13, 15, 17, 300]
In[3]:

Best for Clean, Normal Data Noisy, Skewed Data
Use Case Simple stats, reports Medical, finance, ML input

Situation Use This Mean
Sensor data with noise Trimmed Mean
Income or salary analysis Trimmed Mean
Clean scientific experiments Normal Mean
Initial quick reports Normal Mean
  • 6 Weighted Mean
    • Weighted Mean aik aisi average hai jahan har value ki apni importance (weight) hoti hai.
    • Har value ko uske weight se multiply kiya jata hai, phir total weight se divide kiya jata hai.
    • Jab har value ka barabar importance na ho weighted mean use hota hai.
In[18]:
values = [60, 70, 80]
weights = [1, 2, 3]
In[41]:
sm = 0
for v, w in zip(values, weights):
    sm += v * w
wm = sm / sum(weights)
wm
Out[41]:
73.33333333333333
Visualize Weighted Mean And Differences in Normal Means | Weighted Mean

In[45]:
# Weighted Mean Calculation
weighted_mean = sum(df["Values"] * df["Weights"]) / sum(df["Weights"])
normal_mean = df["Values"].mean()

# Plot

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.barplot(
    x="Values",
    y="Weights",
    data=df,
    hue="Values",
    palette="Blues",
    legend=False,
    edgecolor="black",
)
plt.axvline(
    normal_mean, color="red", linestyle="--", label=f"Normal Mean = {normal_mean:.2f}"
)
plt.axvline(
    weighted_mean,
    color="green",
    linestyle="-",
    label=f"Weighted Mean = {weighted_mean:.2f}",
)
plt.title("Weighted vs Normal Mean")
plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.show()
Feature Normal Mean Weighted Mean
Sab values barabar? Yes No (weight matters)
Kis cheez pe based? Sirf values Value importance
Use kab karein? Equal items Jab kuch items more important hon

Use Case Use Weighted Mean?
GPA calculation Yes
Voting power per state Yes
Survey where responses have different weight Yes
Simple average of marks No (use normal mean)

  • Jab higher values ka zyada weight ho, to weighted mean hamesha normal se upar ya neeche chala jata hai depending on weights.
  • 7 Moving Average
    • Moving Average (ya Rolling Average) aik technique hai jo:
      • Time-series ya sequential data ka smooth trend dekhne ke liye use hoti hai.
      • Ye ek sliding window hoti hai jo current + past values ka average leti hai.
In[44]:
data = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60]
k = 3
In[46]:
def moving_average(data,k):
    points = []
    for i in range(len(data)):
        start = i - k + 1 
        if start >= 0 :
            points.append(sum(data[start:i+1]) / 3)
    return points
In[48]:
moving_average(data,k)
Out[48]:
[20.0, 30.0, 40.0, 50.0]

  • Green Dashed Line = moving average jisme spike smooth ho gaya

  • Agar sensor ne galti se 80C record kiya, to model ko direct dene se wo confused ho jaye ga.

  • Moving average use smooth kar ke dikhata hai ke overall trend normal hi tha.

  • Is tarah:

    • AI model overreact nahi karega
    • Data clean aur stable rahega
Use Benefit
Noise Removal Sudden spikes ko average karta hai
Trend Detection Data ka smooth direction dikhata hai
Feature Engineering ML model ke liye stable features banata hai
Better Visualization Graph samajhne mein asani
Anomaly Detection Jab koi point bahut upar niche ho, to deviation detect hota hai

  • 8 Exponential Moving Average

    • Exponential Moving Average (EMA) aik aisi average technique hai
    • jo recent values ko zyada importance deti hai aur
    • purani values ko gradually kam consider karti hai.

  • Exponential Moving Average sirf pichle kuch values ka average nahi hota,

  • balke har naye data point ka effect zyada hota hai.

  • Isse model ya graph recent changes ko jaldi samajh leta hai.

In[62]:
data = [22, 23, 24, 80, 25, 26]
span = 3
In[65]:
alpha = 2 / (span+1)
alpha
Out[65]:
0.5
In[69]:
prev_ema = 0
ema = []
for i in range(len(data)):
    if i == 0:
        ema.append(data[i])
        prev_ema = data[i]
    else:
        current_ema = alpha * data[i] + (1-alpha) * prev_ema
        ema.append(current_ema)
        prev_ema = current_ema
In[70]:
ema
Out[70]:
[22, 22.5, 23.25, 51.625, 38.3125, 32.15625]

Compare Moving Average | Exponential Moving Average

In[78]:
days = pd.date_range(start="2024-01-01", periods=15)
prices = [100, 102, 105, 101, 98, 97, 99, 103, 110, 112, 111, 109, 107, 108, 106]

df = pd.DataFrame({"Date": days, "Price": prices})

df["SMA_5"] = df["Price"].rolling(window=5).mean()
df["EMA_5"] = df["Price"].ewm(span=5, adjust=False).mean()

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(13, 6))
sns.lineplot(data=df, x="Date", y="Price", label="Original Price", marker="o", color='red')
sns.lineplot(data=df, x="Date", y="SMA_5", label="SMA (5day)", marker="o", linestyle="--", color='blue')
sns.lineplot(data=df, x="Date", y="EMA_5", label="EMA (5day)", marker="o", linestyle="--", color='green')

for i in range(len(df)):
    plt.text(df["Date"][i], df["Price"][i] + 1.2, f"{df['Price'][i]}", color='red', fontsize=9)
    
    if pd.notna(df["SMA_5"][i]):
        plt.text(df["Date"][i], df["SMA_5"][i] + 1.2, f"{df['SMA_5'][i]:.1f}", color='blue', fontsize=9)
    
    plt.text(df["Date"][i], df["EMA_5"][i] - 2.5, f"{df['EMA_5'][i]:.1f}", color='green', fontsize=9)

plt.title("Stock Price with SMA and EMA (5-Day) with Data Labels")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Price")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • SMA(5) ko har naya point ke liye pichlay 5 din ka normal average calculate hota hai equal weight.
  • EMA(5) recent price ko zyada weight deta hai, aur trend changes ko jaldi reflect karta hai.
  • Agar koi sharp spike ya dip aata hai, to:
    • SMA isi mutation ko smoother tarah se show karega,
    • EMA us effect ko thoda zyada, lekin soon-after smooth kar lega.
Feature SMA (Simple Moving Average) EMA (Exponential Moving Average)
Definition Last k values ka average Recent values ko zyada weight deta hai
Weighting Har value ka equal weight Recent values ko zyada weight milta hai
Responsiveness Slow response to recent changes Fast response to recent changes
Noise Handling Better for removing noise Better for capturing short-term changes
Lag (Delay) Zyada lag (delayed response) Kam lag (quicker adjustment to trend)
Calculation Straightforward rolling average Recursive formula based on smoothing factor (alpha)
Best For Long-term stable trends Short-term signals / fast-changing trends
Outlier Reaction Sudden spike ka asar slow hota hai Outlier ka effect zyada hota hai initially
Use in Trading Long-term support/resistance zones Entry/Exit signal detection (crossovers etc.)
Situation / Use Case SMA / EMA? Reason
Long-term trend analysis SMA Stable average, less noise
Short-term signal detection (e.g. trading) EMA Fast reacts to price changes
Health Monitoring (e.g. heartbeat sensor) EMA Glitches ka asar jaldi samjhta
Noise filtering (smooth curve) SMA Equal weight = less volatility
ML Feature for trend EMA Adaptive, dynamic
